  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Can Home Depot copy a car key with a chip if I provide them a blank key with a chip?",
  "response": "Copying a car key that includes a transponder chip (often referred to as a \"chip key\" or \"smart key\") involves more than just duplicating the physical key. The transponder chip must be programmed to communicate correctly with your vehicle's ignition system to allow the car to start. \n\n**Home Depot's Capabilities:**\n\n- **Standard Key Duplication:** Home Depot offers key duplication services for standard (non-programmed) keys, such as basic metal keys without electronic components.\n  \n- **Transponder Key Programming:** While Home Depot does provide key cutting services, programming transponder chips typically requires specialized equipment and software that may not be available at all Home Depot locations. As a result, Home Depot **may not** be able to program a transponder chip even if you provide them with a blank key that already contains a chip.\n\n**Recommended Options for Chip Keys:**\n\n1. **Automotive Locksmiths:** Professional locksmiths who specialize in automotive services are usually equipped to handle transponder key programming. They have the necessary tools and expertise to program the chip to your vehicle's specific immobilizer system.\n\n2. **Dealerships:** Your car's dealership can provide key duplication and programming services. While often more expensive, dealerships have direct access to manufacturer-specific key programming tools and information.\n\n3. **Specialized Key Services:** There are dedicated key service providers that offer both cutting and programming for transponder keys, key fobs, and smart keys.\n\n**Steps to Get a Chip Key Copied:**\n\n1. **Obtain a Compatible Blank Key:** Ensure that the blank key you provide matches your vehicle's make, model, and year. Not all blanks are compatible with every vehicle's transponder system.\n\n2. **Provide Proof of Ownership:** Most reputable services will require proof that you own the vehicle, such as a registration or title, to prevent unauthorized key duplication.\n\n3. **Program the Transponder:** The service provider will program the transponder chip so that it communicates correctly with your car's ignition system.\n\n**Additional Considerations:**\n\n- **Cost:** Transponder key duplication and programming can be more expensive than standard key copying due to the additional technology involved.\n\n- **Time:** Programming may take longer than cutting a standard key, so plan accordingly if you need a replacement quickly.\n\n- **Spare Keys:** It's a good practice to have a spare transponder key programmed in advance to avoid similar issues in the future.\n\n**Conclusion:**\n\nWhile Home Depot can duplicate standard car keys, duplicating and programming a transponder (chip) key typically requires specialized services that are best handled by professional automotive locksmiths or dealerships. It's recommended to contact a local automotive locksmith or your vehicle's dealership to ensure your transponder key is properly copied and programmed.",
